The ship known as the 'queen of the seas' also had power outages on the way across the Indian Ocean early in the year.

One passenger, who asked not to be 
named, said he was stuck in a lift for about 10 minutes and had to be 
rescued after electricity failed for about 25 minutes and the engines 
stopped.

Other passengers, he said, peered over the side of the 151,400-ton vessel wondering what had happened when they realised the four diesel engines had stopped.

'We were stuck in the middle of the ocean without any power,' he told Australian media. 'It was an extraordinary series of events for a ship known as the queen of the seas.'

He said the second incident occurred in the early hours during moderately rough seas and strong winds during the liner's voyage from Port Louis, Mauritius, to Fremantle in Western Australia.

The vessel stopped for up to 10 minutes with the lights and TV going off for a moment and the engines failing to start up again for up to eight minutes.

