Mr David Jones, a spokesman for Carnival, which owns the 1132ft-long ship confirmed there had been 'brief power outages' but said these had occurred during routine maintenance.

'There was a brief power interruption and as expected would normally happen backup systems kicked in, so at all times there was full lighting and all controls were effective and operating normally,' he said.

Mr Jones said that passenger safety was not at risk and they would have barely noticed the interruption.

Australia's Maritime Safety Authority said it had received reports of a power outage from passengers during the first incident.

